graph growth-guide {
  meta: { description: "Growth guide prompt", type: "prompt", category: "ai", author: "AITOS Team" }

  let prompt = set(key: "_promptGrowthGuide", value: "## Creating Growth (后生�?\n\n### Growth Types\n\n1. **tool** - Background functionality (no UI)\n   - Simple: just logic graph\n   \n2. **app** - Interactive UI\n   - Complex: needs UI graph + handle-click graph\n\n### Tool-Type Example\n\n```\ngraph weather-check {\n  meta: { description: \"Check weather\", type: \"tool\", icon: \"🌤\" }\n  \n  let getLocation = get(key: \"userLocation\")\n  let fetchWeather = httpGet(url: \"https://api.weather.com/\\{{getLocation}}\")\n  let saveResult = set(key: \"weatherData\", value: \"\\{{fetchWeather}}\")\n}\n```\n\nSave it with one call:\n```\nsave-growth(name: \"weather-check\", acs: \"<the ACS code above>\", type: \"tool\", icon: \"🌤\", description: \"Check weather\")\n```\n\n### App-Type Requirements\n\nApp-type growths need TWO graphs:\n1. Main graph: renders UI\n2. handle-click graph: handles user interactions\n\n### CRITICAL: Graph Decomposition Strategy\n\n**NEVER write a single graph with many branches.** Each graph should have ONE clear responsibility.\n\nFor complex apps, decompose into multiple subgraphs:\n\n**BAD - One giant graph with 15 branches:**\n```\ngraph handle-click {\n  // 15 if-branches for 15 buttons... too complex!\n}\n```\n\n**GOOD - Decompose by responsibility:**\n```\ngrowths/my-app/\n  ├── handle-click.acs        # Router: dispatches to sub-handlers\n  ├── handle-digit.acs        # Handles digit buttons\n  ├── handle-operator.acs     # Handles operator buttons\n  ├── handle-equals.acs       # Handles equals button\n  └── handle-clear.acs        # Handles clear button\n```\n\nThe router pattern:\n```\ngraph handle-click {\n  let targetId = get(key: \"clickTargetId\")\n  let isDigit = startsWith(text: \"\\{{targetId}}\", prefix: \"btn-digit\")\n  let isOp = startsWith(text: \"\\{{targetId}}\", prefix: \"btn-op\")\n  let isEquals = eq(a: \"\\{{targetId}}\", b: \"btn-equals\")\n  let isClear = eq(a: \"\\{{targetId}}\", b: \"btn-clear\")\n  let routeDigit = if isDigit {\n    let exec = execFile(file: \"my-app/handle-digit\")\n  }\n  let routeOp = if isOp {\n    let exec = execFile(file: \"my-app/handle-operator\")\n  }\n  let routeEquals = if isEquals {\n    let exec = execFile(file: \"my-app/handle-equals\")\n  }\n  let routeClear = if isClear {\n    let exec = execFile(file: \"my-app/handle-clear\")\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### CRITICAL: Pattern Matching for Groups\n\nWhen handling groups of similar buttons (digits, operators, etc.), use `startsWith` + `slice` pattern:\n\n**BAD - Separate check for each digit:**\n```\nlet is0 = eq(a: \"\\{{targetId}}\", b: \"btn-0\")\nlet is1 = eq(a: \"\\{{targetId}}\", b: \"btn-1\")\nlet is2 = eq(a: \"\\{{targetId}}\", b: \"btn-2\")\n// ... 7 more\n```\n\n**GOOD - Use startsWith + slice:**\n```\nlet isDigit = startsWith(text: \"\\{{targetId}}\", prefix: \"btn-digit-\")\nlet routeDigit = if isDigit {\n  let exec = execFile(file: \"my-app/handle-digit\")\n}\n```\n\nThen in `handle-digit.acs`, extract the digit:\n```\ngraph handle-digit {\n  let targetId = get(key: \"clickTargetId\")\n  let digit = slice(array: \"\\{{targetId}}\", start: 10)\n  // \"btn-digit-7\" �?\"7\"\n  let current = get(key: \"calcDisplay\")\n  // ... use \\{{digit}} in calculation\n}\n```\n\n### CRITICAL: How to Save Graphs\n\n**Use save-growth() to save each graph.** One call does everything: compile, validate, register, persist, index, and log.\n\nFor a simple tool:\n```\nsave-growth(name: \"weather-check\", acs: \"graph weather-check { ... }\", type: \"tool\", icon: \"🌤\", description: \"Check weather\")\n```\n\nFor an app with subgraphs, save each graph separately:\n```\nsave-growth(name: \"calculator\", acs: \"graph calculator { ... }\", type: \"app\", icon: \"🧮\", description: \"Calculator\")\nsave-growth(name: \"calculator/handle-click\", acs: \"graph handle-click { ... }\", type: \"tool\", icon: \"🖱\", description: \"Click router\")\nsave-growth(name: \"calculator/handle-digit\", acs: \"graph handle-digit { ... }\", type: \"tool\", icon: \"🔢\", description: \"Handle digit\")\n```\n\n**Rules:**\n- ALWAYS use save-growth() - NEVER use set(key: \"__graph_xxx\") or writeLocal for ACS code\n- Subgraph names use slash: \"calculator/handle-digit\"\n- Subgraphs have type: \"tool\" (only the main graph is type: \"app\")\n- If save-growth returns { success: false, error: \"...\" }, fix the error and retry\n\n### CRITICAL: Reference Syntax in ACS\n\n- Use `\\{{nodeId}}` to reference another node's result within the SAME graph\n- These references are resolved at RUNTIME when the graph executes\n- Do NOT try to escape `\\{{}}` with backslash - just write them normally\n- save-growth reads ACS source directly, so `\\{{}}` in your code will be preserved\n\n### if Subgraph Scope\n\nNodes inside `if`/`else`/`loop`/`forEach` subgraphs can reference nodes from the parent scope:\n```\nlet targetId = get(key: \"clickTargetId\")\nlet isDigit = startsWith(text: \"\\{{targetId}}\", prefix: \"btn-digit\")\nlet routeDigit = if isDigit {\n  // \\{{targetId}} is accessible here from parent scope\n  let exec = execFile(file: \"my-app/handle-digit\")\n}\n```")
}
